[The patient worked in a fisherman's club in a national park, likely in a rural or natural environment where rodent virus reservoirs live. This environment is not described in the above report. The locality where the young man acquired his hantavirus infection is Chubut province, in the foothills of the Andes Mountains.

Although the virus involved in this case is not mentioned, the most likely virus is Andes virus, found in western Argentina in the long-tailed pygmy rice rat host, _Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_. There is also the possibility of infection with Seoul hantavirus, which is widely distributed in the world in brown rats (_Rattus norvegicus_). This virus can also be transmitted directly between people in close physical contact.

The above reveals that the patient is suffering serious respiratory insufficiency and is on mechanical respiration, indicating that this is a case of hantavirus cardiopulmonary syndrome, which can have a case fatality rate of 40%. This syndrome can rapidly become very serious and fatal. - Mod.TY

ProMED map of Chubut Province, Argentina: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8700944,53508.]
